  "text": "# HTTP Health Check Endpoint Implementations Across Kubernetes, Grafana, and Prometheus\n\n## Overview\nThe three projects use different approaches to implement health check endpoints:\n\n## Kubernetes (github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes)\nKubernetes uses a comprehensive health check framework with three distinct endpoints:\n\n### Endpoints\n- **/healthz**: General health status\n- **/livez**: Liveness probe (indicates if the server is still running)\n- **/readyz**: Readiness probe (indicates if the server is ready to accept traffic)\n\n### Implementation Architecture\nThe health check framework is implemented in `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/healthz/healthz.go` and integrated through `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/healthz.go`.\n\n**Key Components:**\n1. **HealthChecker Interface** (line 40-44): Defines the contract for health checks with `Name()` and `Check(req *http.Request)` methods\n\n2. **Built-in Health Checks** (staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/healthz/healthz.go):\n   - **PingHealthz** (line 52): Always returns healthy, serves as a baseline check\n   - **LogHealthz** (line 67): Monitors logging system health, ensures logs are not blocked\n   - **InformerSyncHealthz** (NewInformerSyncHealthz, line 105-109): Waits for cache synchronization of informers\n   - **ShutdownHealthz** (NewShutdownHealthz, line 121-123): Fails when shutdown signal is received\n   - **Custom Named Checks**: Via `NamedCheck()` and `NamedGroupedCheck()` for domain-specific checks\n\n3. **Database Health Checks** - ETcd Integration (staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/options/etcd.go, lines 354-413):\n   - **etcd-health check** (line 359-361): Created via `storagefactory.CreateHealthCheck()`, checks connectivity and health of etcd backend\n   - **etcd-readiness check** (line 367-369): Created via `storagefactory.CreateReadyCheck()`, ensures etcd is ready to serve requests\n   - **Multi-server overrides** (lines 371-411): Supports multiple etcd server configurations with separate health checks for each override\n\n4. **Handler Installation** (staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/healthz.go, lines 124-140):\n   - `installHealthz()` installs the /healthz endpoint\n   - `installReadyz()` installs the /readyz endpoint with a callback for lifecycle signals\n   - `installLivez()` installs the /livez endpoint\n   - Each endpoint can have multiple health checks aggregated via `healthCheckRegistry`\n\n5. **Grace Periods and Delayed Checks** (healthz.go, lines 142-167):\n   - Livez checks support grace periods during startup (via `delayedHealthCheck`)\n   - Readyz has no grace period - must pass before server accepts traffic\n   - Healthz serves backward compatibility\n\n### Configuration (staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/config.go, lines 197-204)\nThe server config holds three separate check lists:\n- `HealthzChecks`: For /healthz endpoint\n- `LivezChecks`: For /livez endpoint  \n- `ReadyzChecks`: For /readyz endpoint\n\nMethods to add checks:\n- `AddHealthChecks()` (lines 579-586): Adds to healthz, livez, and readyz\n- `AddReadyzChecks()` (lines 588-592): Adds only to readyz\n- `AddLivezChecks()`: Adds only to livez\n\n## Prometheus (github.com/prometheus/prometheus)\nPrometheus uses a simpler, state-based approach:\n\n### Endpoints\n- **/-/healthy**: HTTP health status\n- **/-/ready**: HTTP readiness status\n\n### Implementation (web/web.go)\n\n1. **Simple Response Handlers** (lines 591-604):\n   - `/-/healthy` (line 591-597): Always returns 200 OK with message \"{AppName} is Healthy\"\n   - `/-/ready` (line 598-604): Wrapped by `readyf()` middleware that checks internal state\n   - Both support GET and HEAD methods\n\n2. **State-Based Readiness** (lines 658-677):\n   - `testReady()` function checks `h.ready` atomic value\n   - Returns 200 OK if state is `Ready`\n   - Returns 503 Service Unavailable if state is `NotReady` or `Stopping`\n   - Sets `X-Prometheus-Stopping` header to indicate shutdown state\n\n3. **Ready States** (web/web.go):\n   - `Ready`: Server is operational and ready for requests\n   - `NotReady`: Server is initializing\n   - `Stopping`: Server is shutting down\n\n4. **No Complex Health Checks**: Unlike Kubernetes, Prometheus doesn't perform detailed component checks. It relies on a simple atomic ready flag that must be set externally.\n\n## Grafana (github.com/grafana/grafana)\nGrafana adopts Kubernetes' health check framework:\n\n### Endpoints\n- **/livez**: Via proxy to Kubernetes apiserver\n- **/readyz**: Via proxy to Kubernetes apiserver\n- **/healthz**: Via proxy to Kubernetes apiserver\n\n### Implementation (pkg/services/apiserver/service.go, lines 211-214)\nGrafana doesn't implement custom health checks but instead proxies the endpoints to its embedded Kubernetes apiserver:\n\n```\ns.rr.Group(\"/livez\", proxyHandler)\ns.rr.Group(\"/readyz\", proxyHandler)\ns.rr.Group(\"/healthz\", proxyHandler)\n```\n\nThe `proxyHandler` forwards requests to `s.GenericAPIServer`, which is a standard Kubernetes apiserver that inherits all its health check infrastructure.\n\n### Benefits of Grafana's Approach\n- Reuses battle-tested Kubernetes health check framework\n- Automatic support for etcd health checks\n- Consistent with Kubernetes ecosystem expectations\n- Supports informer sync checks for APIServer resources\n\n## Key Differences\n\n1. **Complexity**: Kubernetes > Grafana > Prometheus\n2. **Dependency Checks**:\n   - Kubernetes: Etcd connectivity, informer synchronization, logging\n   - Prometheus: Simple atomic flag\n   - Grafana: Inherits Kubernetes checks\n3. **Graceful Shutdown**:\n   - Kubernetes: Dedicated shutdown checks\n   - Prometheus: Separate stopping state\n   - Grafana: Uses Kubernetes mechanism\n4. **Response Codes**:\n   - All three return 200 for healthy/ready states\n   - All return 5xx for not-ready states\n5. **Endpoint Naming**:\n   - Kubernetes/Grafana: /healthz, /livez, /readyz (REST style)\n   - Prometheus: /-/healthy, /-/ready (special prefix style)\n"
}

